column13: Jose: The MSE-evaluated HCR is provided as one of the catch scenarios from which managers can choose. For the advice relevant to 2021, the EU Commission requested ICES to provide advice based on the MSY approach, but the HCR was still one of the options presented in the advice sheet (see http://ices.dk/sites/pub/Publication%20Reports/Advice/2020/2020/pil.27.8c9a.pdf)

I would argue no because case-specific examples of the EU-MAP have not been simulation tested within an MSE - see comment in Cell A40. This one is tricky. If you read the advice sheet (http://ices.dk/sites/pub/Publication%20Reports/Advice/2020/2020/spr.27.22-32.pdf) you would think there is a plan in place, and the plan as been evaluated "An EU multiannual plan (MAP) in place for stocks in the Baltic Sea includes sprat (EU, 2016, 2019). The advice, based on the FMSY ranges used in the management plan, is considered precautionary." However, although there were generic simulations to look at the MAP in general, case-specific examples were not necessarily evaluated (I don't know of any), and when the statement is made that it is "considered precautionary", it is because of the way the Fmsy ranges were defined using software that cannot be considered conducting an MSE (the software is used to define reference points and is extremely limited in terms of sources of uncertainty considered - if you are interested you can have a look at the WKMSYREF series of reports, particularly 3 and 4). So I would not consider an EU MAPs to have been evaluated within an MSE (unless it is specifically stated such evaluations have been conducted, which I doubt). This applies to all cases where EU MAPs are used.

column9: There is no shortage of management plans evaluated for NSAS herring, and the latest evaluation is given in column H. However, this is a jointly-managed stock (EU and Norway, soon to become EU, UK and Norway) and the different parties have not agreed a management plan, so ICES advises according to their next best option, i.e. their MSY approach.

column10:
It's a no for this one, according to the latest advice sheet (http://ices.dk/sites/pub/Publication%20Reports/Advice/2019/2019/hom.27.2a4a5b6a7a-ce-k8.pdf).
That said, there have been past MSE evaluations of HCRs for this stock, and an MSE-evaluated management plan (found to be precautionary only in the short-term) was used to provide advice for the years 2008-2010 (potentially also 2011), although the management plan continued to be a management option, at least until 2013.
